[h1]Working with Pseudo Elements [/h1]

Pseudo elements are used to select specific parts of an element.
There are five pseudo elements in CSS, each starting with a double colon ([b]::[/b]):

[b]::first-line[/b] - the first line of the text in a selector
[b]::first-letter[/b] - the first letter of the text in a selector
[b]::selection[/b] - selects the portion of an element that is selected by a user
[b]::before [/b]- inserts some content before an element
[b]::after[/b] - inserts some content after an element

In the example below, the [b]::first-line[/b] pseudo element is used to style the first line of our text: [code format="css" codeId="593"]p[b]::first-line[/b] {
   color: #589432;
}[/code]
[b]Result: [/b][img id="2680" width="100%"]
The [b]::selection[/b] pseudo element styles the selected text: [code format="css" codeId="594"][b]p::-moz-selection[/b] {
   background: #8bc34a;
   color: #fff;
}[/code]
[b]Result: [/b] [img id="2681" width="100%"]
[note]The[b] -moz-[/b] prefix is used, as the :[b]:selection[/b] element is not supported by Mozilla yet.[/note]

quizzes.question:
Add an image prior to the paragraph using a pseudo element.
[!raw!]
p::{0}{ 
   content: {1}("img.jpg");
}
